1
00:00:04,047 --> 00:00:05,744
NARRATOR: Previously onWhy Women Kill...

2
00:00:05,788 --> 00:00:08,965
-This must be Mr. Hemple. -The guy whose life you ruined.

3
00:00:09,009 --> 00:00:10,575
You're going to pay for what you did to me, Loomis.

4
00:00:10,619 --> 00:00:12,447
[grunting, groaning]

5
00:00:12,490 --> 00:00:14,362
Don't you touch him!

6
00:00:14,405 --> 00:00:15,841
Hey! Stop.

7
00:00:15,885 --> 00:00:18,018
-Let me see. -Okay. I'm fine.

8
00:00:18,975 --> 00:00:20,585
Rita is coming to my home?

9
00:00:20,629 --> 00:00:22,283
GRACE: With the entire nominating committee.

10
00:00:22,326 --> 00:00:23,806
Surprise inspection.

11
00:00:23,849 --> 00:00:24,981
Ladies.

12
00:00:25,025 --> 00:00:26,287
ALL: Hello.

13
00:00:26,330 --> 00:00:27,810
What a surprise.

14
00:00:27,853 --> 00:00:29,246
I admire women who try to remake themselves.

15
00:00:29,290 --> 00:00:31,553
Does that mean you'll let me be in the club?

16
00:00:31,596 --> 00:00:33,120
CATHERINE: I think you're responsible

17
00:00:33,163 --> 00:00:34,904
for his fall down the stairs.

18
00:00:34,947 --> 00:00:37,472
Once I can prove that, I will destroy you.

19
00:00:37,515 --> 00:00:38,516
A photo of Catherine

20
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:39,648
in bed with a young buck

21
00:00:39,691 --> 00:00:40,997
would disinherit her.

22
00:00:41,041 --> 00:00:43,608
That scarf looks lovely on you.

23
00:00:43,652 --> 00:00:45,349
I-I'm sorry. Is this person a friend of yours?

24
00:00:45,393 --> 00:00:46,872
I'm his lover.

25
00:00:46,916 --> 00:00:49,049
You cheated on me with that?

26
00:00:49,092 --> 00:00:51,094
What's her name? She humiliated me.

27
00:00:51,138 --> 00:00:52,356
I want to see her punished.

28
00:00:52,400 --> 00:00:53,879
RITA: I think Alma

29
00:00:53,923 --> 00:00:56,534
is absolutely Elysian Park Garden Club material.

30
00:00:57,579 --> 00:00:59,798
MARTHA: I'm falling apart.

31
00:00:59,842 --> 00:01:02,366
Oh, but you don't want to hear how sick I am.

32
00:01:02,410 --> 00:01:03,759
But I do.

33
00:01:03,802 --> 00:01:05,935
I really do.

34
00:01:10,331 --> 00:01:12,898
NARRATOR: Her name was Harriet.

35
00:01:14,117 --> 00:01:16,815
Years earlier, before her illness,

36
00:01:16,859 --> 00:01:19,644
she'd been a schoolteacher.

37
00:01:20,819 --> 00:01:22,517
So it was only natural

38
00:01:22,560 --> 00:01:25,955
she would want to impart one last lesson.

39
00:01:27,087 --> 00:01:30,438
If you live long enough, you will lose someone you love.

40
00:01:32,004 --> 00:01:36,183
Some people f-fall apart when death knocks on their door.

41
00:01:36,226 --> 00:01:39,447
They shed buckets of tears.

42
00:01:39,490 --> 00:01:41,797
Well...

43
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:44,104
I say it's a waste of water.

44
00:01:46,106 --> 00:01:48,586
Light that candle first.

45
00:01:50,371 --> 00:01:52,677
We should simply thank God

46
00:01:52,721 --> 00:01:54,810
for the time we had with those we cared for.

47
00:01:54,853 --> 00:01:57,291
The ones who gave our life meaning.

48
00:01:59,380 --> 00:02:02,209
Let's have music, too. Hmm?

49
00:02:02,252 --> 00:02:04,515
Something Italian, I think.

50
00:02:06,865 --> 00:02:08,867
[soft music playing]

51
00:02:10,956 --> 00:02:14,699
My point is, I'm not afraid to die.

52
00:02:14,743 --> 00:02:17,528
So don't dwell in grief once I've gone.

53
00:02:17,572 --> 00:02:20,140
I will be finally free of suffering.

54
00:02:20,183 --> 00:02:22,185
That is something to celebrate.

55
00:02:25,275 --> 00:02:28,017
Is the syringe ready, Bertram?

56
00:02:29,323 --> 00:02:31,107
Yes, Mummy.

57
00:02:31,151 --> 00:02:32,543
Good.

58
00:02:33,849 --> 00:02:35,416
Let us begin.

59
00:02:39,463 --> 00:02:41,639
You put the needle in...

60
00:02:41,683 --> 00:02:43,424
where I point.

61
00:02:43,467 --> 00:02:45,208
I would do it myself,

62
00:02:45,252 --> 00:02:47,558
but you know what this disease has done to my hands.

63
00:03:05,881 --> 00:03:09,450
It's a glorious thing you've done tonight.

64
00:03:09,493 --> 00:03:12,235
And always remember that.

65
00:03:12,279 --> 00:03:14,455
Remember...

66
00:03:14,498 --> 00:03:18,023
only the best sons send their mothers to heaven.

67
00:03:22,724 --> 00:03:24,726
♪

68
00:03:32,603 --> 00:03:34,605
♪

69
00:03:57,062 --> 00:03:59,456
NARRATOR: It was not uncommon for Bertram Fillcot

70
00:03:59,500 --> 00:04:01,676
to dream of his mother.

71
00:04:02,720 --> 00:04:06,333
So he wasn't at all surprised to see her that night.

72
00:04:08,335 --> 00:04:11,599
But he was a bit startled to discover...

73
00:04:12,643 --> 00:04:14,732
...that she'd brought company.

74
00:04:17,648 --> 00:04:18,736
[gasps]

75
00:04:20,825 --> 00:04:24,307
Bertram knew instantly why they'd come,

76
00:04:24,351 --> 00:04:26,744
and what they expected of him.

77
00:04:33,185 --> 00:04:34,622
Bertie.

78
00:04:34,665 --> 00:04:36,058
What are you doing up?

79
00:04:36,101 --> 00:04:38,060
I d... I couldn't sleep.

80
00:04:38,103 --> 00:04:39,453
You look pale.

81
00:04:39,496 --> 00:04:41,106
Are you ill?

82
00:04:41,150 --> 00:04:43,979
-No, I... -Hmm.

83
00:04:44,022 --> 00:04:46,198
-I had a dream. -Hmm.

84
00:04:46,242 --> 00:04:47,635
Martha Westcott was in it.

85
00:04:48,636 --> 00:04:49,680
Joan's aunt?

86
00:04:49,724 --> 00:04:51,682
Why dream about her?

87
00:04:51,726 --> 00:04:53,162
We spoke for a long time yesterday,

88
00:04:53,205 --> 00:04:55,251
while you were busy with the ladies from the Garden Club.

89
00:04:55,295 --> 00:04:56,644
ALMA: Hmm.

90
00:04:56,687 --> 00:04:59,429
And she confessed to me that she's seriously ill.

91
00:05:02,737 --> 00:05:04,391
Suffering from cancer.

92
00:05:04,434 --> 00:05:05,870
-No! -Alma,

93
00:05:05,914 --> 00:05:07,350
she practically asked me to kill her.

94
00:05:07,394 --> 00:05:10,048
If you could hear how much she missed her dead husband...

95
00:05:10,092 --> 00:05:12,094
Well, you're not going to arrange the reunion.

96
00:05:12,137 --> 00:05:13,704
Can't we at least discuss it?

97
00:05:13,748 --> 00:05:16,707
You gave me your solemn vow you'd give up your little hobby.

98
00:05:16,751 --> 00:05:18,056
I'm trying to.

99
00:05:18,100 --> 00:05:19,536
But the urge...

100
00:05:19,580 --> 00:05:21,712
-It's returned. -Oh. [scoffs]

101
00:05:21,756 --> 00:05:23,323
I'm just worried if I don't do something to satisfy it soon,

102
00:05:23,366 --> 00:05:25,020
I might have a complete mental breakdown.

103
00:05:25,063 --> 00:05:26,456
Nonsense.

104
00:05:26,500 --> 00:05:28,066
That's all in your head.

105
00:05:29,285 --> 00:05:30,721
Oh. Well, if that's the case,

106
00:05:30,765 --> 00:05:32,506
perhaps I should talk to a psychiatrist.

107
00:05:35,247 --> 00:05:36,814
Have you lost your mind?

108
00:05:36,858 --> 00:05:38,990
That would be the topic of conversation, yes.

109
00:05:39,034 --> 00:05:40,731
Psychiatrists gossip just like everyone else.

110
00:05:40,775 --> 00:05:42,472
The risk is far too great.

111
00:05:42,516 --> 00:05:44,909
Well, I need to do something to rid me of this compulsion.

112
00:05:44,953 --> 00:05:47,172
Bertram, I don't want to discuss this.

113
00:05:47,216 --> 00:05:48,957
Please, can we just go back to bed?

114
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:50,393
I'm exhausted.

115
00:05:50,437 --> 00:05:52,221
Yeah, I'm sorry.

116
00:05:52,264 --> 00:05:54,266
Uh...

117
00:05:54,310 --> 00:05:55,877
I'll be up in a moment.

118
00:06:07,105 --> 00:06:08,368
Operator?

119
00:06:08,411 --> 00:06:09,804
Yes, um...

120
00:06:09,847 --> 00:06:12,197
I'd like the number, please, for a Timothy Keegan.

121
00:06:13,329 --> 00:06:15,287
Um, I believe he now lives in Oxnard.

122
00:06:16,767 --> 00:06:18,813
Yes. Yes, I'll hold.

123
00:06:22,904 --> 00:06:24,688
[giggling]

124
00:06:24,732 --> 00:06:26,386
Yes.

125
00:06:26,429 --> 00:06:28,039
[giggling]: Right.

126
00:06:28,083 --> 00:06:29,911
Oh, thanks, Amy.

127
00:06:29,954 --> 00:06:32,304
You won't be sorry you changed your vote.

128
00:06:32,348 --> 00:06:34,829
She'll be a great addition to our club.

129
00:06:34,872 --> 00:06:36,439
Yes.

130
00:06:36,483 --> 00:06:38,398
I'll see you at lunch.

131
00:06:39,486 --> 00:06:41,270
Oh, 11 votes.

132
00:06:41,313 --> 00:06:42,358
It's almost done.

133
00:06:42,402 --> 00:06:44,795
You're looking evil today.

134
00:06:44,839 --> 00:06:46,231
What are you up to?

135
00:06:46,275 --> 00:06:47,711
Everywhere I turn, lately,

136
00:06:47,755 --> 00:06:50,105
people are trying to humiliate me.

137
00:06:50,148 --> 00:06:52,281
So I've been forced to wreak a little havoc.

138
00:06:52,324 --> 00:06:54,109
Get a bit of revenge.

139
00:06:54,152 --> 00:06:55,458
What do you want revenge for?

140
00:06:55,502 --> 00:06:57,852
You've got a fur coat, a fancy car.

141
00:06:57,895 --> 00:06:59,462
Most people would kill for your life.

142
00:06:59,506 --> 00:07:02,944
I'm looking for sympathy, Isabel, not perspective.

143
00:07:11,605 --> 00:07:13,041
Please, Papa.

144
00:07:13,084 --> 00:07:14,912
You must squeeze the ball.

145
00:07:14,956 --> 00:07:17,262
The doctors say it will help you regain control of your body.

146
00:07:18,394 --> 00:07:19,395
Miss Castillo?

147
00:07:19,439 --> 00:07:21,049
Hello.

148
00:07:21,092 --> 00:07:23,051
Scooter, from the dry cleaners.

149
00:07:24,531 --> 00:07:25,793
CATHARINE: Oh, of course.

150
00:07:25,836 --> 00:07:27,142
It's so nice to see you.

151
00:07:27,185 --> 00:07:28,491
Out for a stroll?

152
00:07:28,535 --> 00:07:30,493
I always bring my Papa here

153
00:07:30,537 --> 00:07:32,364
for his special exercises.

154
00:07:32,408 --> 00:07:33,888
You're a good daughter.

155
00:07:33,931 --> 00:07:36,064
Nothing matters more than family.

156
00:07:36,107 --> 00:07:38,283
That's what my mom used to say,

157
00:07:38,327 --> 00:07:39,981
before she died.

158
00:07:41,069 --> 00:07:42,984
Oh, Papa. You dropped the ball.

159
00:07:46,988 --> 00:07:49,860
I seemed to have got some mustard on my shirt.

160
00:07:49,904 --> 00:07:51,383
You don't happen to have a hankie?

161
00:07:51,427 --> 00:07:52,472
Oh, I think so.

162
00:07:58,390 --> 00:08:00,567
When did you lose your mama?

163
00:08:00,610 --> 00:08:02,960
I was ten.

164
00:08:03,004 --> 00:08:04,527
Oh. So young.

165
00:08:04,571 --> 00:08:06,137
I loved her so much.

166
00:08:06,181 --> 00:08:07,922
We had so much fun.

167
00:08:09,053 --> 00:08:11,969
Well, I... I don't seem to be helping much.

168
00:08:12,013 --> 00:08:14,058
Oh, uh...

169
00:08:15,756 --> 00:08:18,019
Try the water fountain.

170
00:08:29,639 --> 00:08:31,728
SCOOTER: So...

171
00:08:32,903 --> 00:08:34,383
Do you go to the movies?

172
00:08:34,426 --> 00:08:37,125
Oh, yes. I-I love foreign films.

173
00:08:37,168 --> 00:08:39,257
I actually enjoy reading subtitles.

174
00:08:40,302 --> 00:08:42,304
You know, maybe we could...

175
00:08:42,347 --> 00:08:44,567
Oh. What am I saying?

176
00:08:44,611 --> 00:08:45,568
You don't even know me.

177
00:08:45,612 --> 00:08:47,657
Well, I know

178
00:08:47,701 --> 00:08:50,355
you're a very polite young man.

179
00:08:50,399 --> 00:08:51,748
And, uh,

180
00:08:51,792 --> 00:08:54,185
there is an Italian movie I've been dying to see.

181
00:08:54,229 --> 00:08:57,101
[stammers] I believe it starts at 6:30.

182
00:08:58,712 --> 00:09:00,278
I'll pick you up at 6:00.

183
00:09:01,410 --> 00:09:03,064
[giggling]

184
00:09:03,107 --> 00:09:05,806
SCOOTER: Nice to meet you, sir.

185
00:09:07,068 --> 00:09:08,025
Oh, Papa.

186
00:09:08,069 --> 00:09:09,853
You're squeezing so hard.

187
00:09:09,897 --> 00:09:11,986
You must be getting your strength back.

188
00:09:13,814 --> 00:09:15,816
[bicycle bell rings]

189
00:09:22,605 --> 00:09:24,564
-Morning, Mrs. Fillcot. -Hello.

190
00:09:24,607 --> 00:09:27,218
Boy, your garden sure does look lovely.

191
00:09:27,262 --> 00:09:28,568
Oh. [chuckles]

192
00:09:28,611 --> 00:09:31,788
Thank you, Eddie. It truly is my pride and joy.

193
00:09:31,832 --> 00:09:33,268
-I'll bet. -Hmm.

194
00:09:33,311 --> 00:09:34,399
So I got a telegram for you.

195
00:09:34,443 --> 00:09:36,010
A telegram?

196
00:09:36,053 --> 00:09:37,707
For me?

197
00:09:37,751 --> 00:09:39,274
Oh, dear.

198
00:09:40,405 --> 00:09:42,103
[clears throat]

199
00:09:43,539 --> 00:09:45,541
RITA: Congratulations to our new member.

200
00:09:45,585 --> 00:09:47,369
Luncheon reception today at 2:00.

201
00:09:47,412 --> 00:09:49,023
[gasps]

202
00:09:49,066 --> 00:09:50,764
Is it bad news?

203
00:09:50,807 --> 00:09:53,201
-[squeals] -Whoa.

204
00:09:54,681 --> 00:09:56,291
Dee! Bertram!

205
00:09:56,334 --> 00:09:58,206
-Where are you? -In here.

206
00:09:58,249 --> 00:09:59,337
Is everything okay?

207
00:09:59,381 --> 00:10:00,817
Everything's spectacular.

208
00:10:00,861 --> 00:10:03,298
-I've been accepted into the Garden Club. -No.

209
00:10:03,341 --> 00:10:05,126
Telegram just arrived.

210
00:10:05,169 --> 00:10:06,693
Telegram?

211
00:10:06,736 --> 00:10:08,216
Why didn't they just call?

212
00:10:08,259 --> 00:10:09,391
Who cares?

213
00:10:09,434 --> 00:10:11,306
My dream's coming true.

214
00:10:11,349 --> 00:10:13,003
The reception is this afternoon.

215
00:10:13,047 --> 00:10:14,526
I need to find something to wear,

216
00:10:14,570 --> 00:10:16,224
drive into town and get my hair done.

217
00:10:16,267 --> 00:10:18,139
Bertie, where are you? I have news!

218
00:10:18,182 --> 00:10:19,401
Uh, Daddy's gone.

219
00:10:19,444 --> 00:10:20,663
Gone where?

220
00:10:20,707 --> 00:10:22,447
He left you a note.

221
00:10:22,491 --> 00:10:25,276
He took the bus to meet someone down in Oxnard.

222
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:26,887
He'll be back tomorrow.

223
00:10:26,930 --> 00:10:29,977
I'll grab the car keys, and you can drop me off at work.

224
00:10:32,327 --> 00:10:35,330
Who on Earth does he know in Oxnard?

225
00:10:43,425 --> 00:10:45,166
[door opens]

226
00:10:46,210 --> 00:10:47,342
Bertram Fillcot.

227
00:10:47,385 --> 00:10:49,605
What a sight for sore eyes.

228
00:10:49,649 --> 00:10:50,911
I'm surprised you recognized me.

229
00:10:50,954 --> 00:10:52,913
It's been what? 20 years?

230
00:10:52,956 --> 00:10:55,567
I was thrilled to get your call.

231
00:10:55,611 --> 00:10:58,179
I-I was a bit curious as to what prompted it,

232
00:10:58,222 --> 00:11:00,268
after such a long time.

233
00:11:00,311 --> 00:11:02,574
Yes, well... to be honest, um...

234
00:11:02,618 --> 00:11:05,534
I'm in desperate need of someone to talk to.

235
00:11:05,577 --> 00:11:07,362
Ah.

236
00:11:07,405 --> 00:11:09,625
I had a feeling.

237
00:11:14,456 --> 00:11:16,588
Oh. Hey, Max. You got a phone call.

238
00:11:16,632 --> 00:11:18,286
-Who is it? -Some lady.

239
00:11:18,329 --> 00:11:19,548
Wouldn't give her name,

240
00:11:19,591 --> 00:11:21,463
but she insisted on talking to the owner.

241
00:11:21,506 --> 00:11:23,378
Hello.

242
00:11:25,772 --> 00:11:27,077
So you're sure you're okay?

243
00:11:27,121 --> 00:11:29,079
I went to see Dr. Rice,

244
00:11:29,123 --> 00:11:31,212
and he said it was just a bump on the noggin.

245
00:11:31,255 --> 00:11:33,170
But he's going to run some tests, to be sure.

246
00:11:33,214 --> 00:11:34,868
Good.

247
00:11:34,911 --> 00:11:36,826
So you got plans for tonight?

248
00:11:36,870 --> 00:11:38,872
There's this guy I've been seeing.

249
00:11:38,915 --> 00:11:40,917
I'm hoping he'll take me some place nice.

250
00:11:40,961 --> 00:11:42,440
No such luck.

251
00:11:42,484 --> 00:11:44,181
I think he wants you to come to his apartment tonight.

252
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:47,402
Does he really?

253
00:11:47,445 --> 00:11:49,056
Not what you think.

254
00:11:49,099 --> 00:11:50,579
I'm going to make you dinner.

255
00:11:50,622 --> 00:11:53,495
Stop the presses. You cook?

256
00:11:53,538 --> 00:11:55,932
Let's just say I know my way around a pork chop.

257
00:11:55,976 --> 00:11:59,109
Oh, and I'm going to be making you tapioca for dessert.

258
00:11:59,153 --> 00:12:01,285
I don't know how, but...

259
00:12:01,329 --> 00:12:03,287
you just got better-looking.

260
00:12:03,331 --> 00:12:05,289
[Dee chuckles]

261
00:12:05,333 --> 00:12:07,335
Ma'am, listen. I don't tolerate my waitresses

262
00:12:07,378 --> 00:12:08,858
being rude to the customers.

263
00:12:08,902 --> 00:12:11,121
I promise, I will handle this.

264
00:12:11,165 --> 00:12:12,688
Now, did you get her name?

265
00:12:12,732 --> 00:12:14,734
No? Well, can you describe her to me?

266
00:12:16,213 --> 00:12:18,259
She was blonde and...

267
00:12:18,302 --> 00:12:20,130
heavyset.

268
00:12:20,174 --> 00:12:21,958
Some might use the word "fat,"

269
00:12:22,002 --> 00:12:23,481
but I don't like to be cruel.

270
00:12:24,831 --> 00:12:27,485
[Dee laughing]

271
00:12:46,069 --> 00:12:47,767
♪

272
00:12:59,691 --> 00:13:01,389
Hello, ladies.

273
00:13:01,432 --> 00:13:03,347
Am I the last one to arrive?

274
00:13:03,391 --> 00:13:06,046
How rude to be late to my own induction.

275
00:13:06,089 --> 00:13:08,526
I-I couldn't decide what to wear.

276
00:13:08,570 --> 00:13:10,224
I knew there would be photos taken, so...

277
00:13:10,267 --> 00:13:13,140
Uh, what is the protocol? Do I...

278
00:13:14,228 --> 00:13:15,490
...make a little speech, like at the Oscars?

279
00:13:15,533 --> 00:13:17,753
Alma, what are you...?

280
00:13:17,797 --> 00:13:21,844
All I really want to say is how happy

281
00:13:21,888 --> 00:13:25,848
and how proud you've made me.

282
00:13:25,892 --> 00:13:27,284
Alma, stop.

283
00:13:29,330 --> 00:13:31,027
What's wrong?

284
00:13:31,071 --> 00:13:32,376
You shouldn't be here.

285
00:13:32,420 --> 00:13:34,161
But...

286
00:13:34,204 --> 00:13:36,293
I was invited. I-I'm the new member.

287
00:13:37,338 --> 00:13:38,730
No, dear.

288
00:13:38,774 --> 00:13:40,558
[stammers] We voted. Um...

289
00:13:41,951 --> 00:13:44,475
Ada Coy was chosen.

290
00:13:48,784 --> 00:13:50,873
I-I received a telegram.

291
00:13:50,917 --> 00:13:53,702
And-and it said "congratulations"

292
00:13:53,745 --> 00:13:55,356
and it said to come here for lunch.

293
00:13:55,399 --> 00:13:57,358
A telegram?

294
00:13:59,186 --> 00:14:01,405
Rita?

295
00:14:01,449 --> 00:14:03,407
Oh, dear.

296
00:14:04,844 --> 00:14:07,803
My maid must have gotten mixed up and...

297
00:14:07,847 --> 00:14:10,327
sent the telegram to you.

298
00:14:10,371 --> 00:14:13,287
Ada and Alma are such similar names.

299
00:14:13,330 --> 00:14:15,898
I am so...

300
00:14:15,942 --> 00:14:18,379
so terribly sorry for the mix-up.

301
00:14:18,422 --> 00:14:20,990
But please, have a drink at the bar,

302
00:14:21,034 --> 00:14:24,472
and some food, if you'd like.

303
00:14:24,515 --> 00:14:26,866
On me, of course.

304
00:14:34,090 --> 00:14:35,918
No, I should go.

305
00:14:40,401 --> 00:14:41,881
RITA: Uh...

306
00:14:47,495 --> 00:14:49,497
♪

307
00:15:15,088 --> 00:15:17,264
[indistinct chatter]

308
00:15:17,307 --> 00:15:18,830
[Dee sighs]

309
00:15:18,874 --> 00:15:19,962
What's going on?

310
00:15:20,006 --> 00:15:21,921
Max just gave me the heave-ho.

311
00:15:21,964 --> 00:15:22,965
Why?

312
00:15:23,009 --> 00:15:24,924
Some customer complained about me.

313
00:15:24,967 --> 00:15:27,578
She told Max I insulted her.

314
00:15:27,622 --> 00:15:28,971
That's ridiculous.

315
00:15:29,015 --> 00:15:31,191
You're nice to everybody.

316
00:15:31,234 --> 00:15:33,715
-It had to have been one of the other girls. -No.

317
00:15:33,758 --> 00:15:35,717
She said it was the fat girl.

318
00:15:35,760 --> 00:15:37,284
And then demanded Max fire me.

319
00:15:37,327 --> 00:15:38,720
Who the hell is this broad?

320
00:15:38,763 --> 00:15:40,591
She wouldn't give Max her name.

321
00:15:40,635 --> 00:15:43,159
But he still believed her, so to hell with him...

322
00:15:43,203 --> 00:15:45,640
and this crummy job.

323
00:15:45,683 --> 00:15:49,296
Is there some lady out there who hates your guts?

324
00:15:51,254 --> 00:15:53,039
Aw, geez.

325
00:15:54,257 --> 00:15:56,259
[exhales sharply]

326
00:15:58,044 --> 00:16:01,047
Would you like a spot of tea before dinner?

327
00:16:01,090 --> 00:16:03,310
Ah. Well, I thought I might provide

328
00:16:03,353 --> 00:16:06,139
a little liquid refreshment.

329
00:16:06,182 --> 00:16:09,272
I remember how much you used to like whiskey.

330
00:16:09,316 --> 00:16:11,796
Bertie, that's very thoughtful, but, um...

331
00:16:11,840 --> 00:16:13,494
I don't drink anymore.

332
00:16:13,537 --> 00:16:15,017
Oh. You don't?

333
00:16:15,061 --> 00:16:17,759
Over the years, I realized I had a problem.

334
00:16:17,802 --> 00:16:21,806
Got so bad, I was sipping communion wine between Masses.

335
00:16:21,850 --> 00:16:23,199
Father.

336
00:16:23,243 --> 00:16:25,985
Took me ages to quit, but I finally did.

337
00:16:26,028 --> 00:16:27,899
Thank the Heavenly Lord.

338
00:16:27,943 --> 00:16:28,900
Well, good for you.

339
00:16:28,944 --> 00:16:29,901
Oh, well.

340
00:16:29,945 --> 00:16:31,991
A cup of tea will be fine.

341
00:16:32,034 --> 00:16:34,645
So, what did you want to talk about?

342
00:16:35,690 --> 00:16:37,431
I know you've retired, um...

343
00:16:37,474 --> 00:16:39,389
Relax.

344
00:16:39,433 --> 00:16:42,218
The seal of the confessional still holds.

345
00:16:42,262 --> 00:16:43,959
Good. Good. Good.

346
00:16:44,003 --> 00:16:47,832
Does your, uh, problem involve that nice wife of yours?

347
00:16:47,876 --> 00:16:49,443
-What was her name? -Alma.

348
00:16:49,486 --> 00:16:52,576
Yes, we've been having some marital difficulties.

349
00:16:52,620 --> 00:16:54,013
She's upset with me.

350
00:16:54,056 --> 00:16:55,666
Well, I'm curious.

351
00:16:55,710 --> 00:16:59,061
Why not discuss this situation with, uh, your parish priest?

352
00:16:59,105 --> 00:17:01,368
Why come so far to see me?

353
00:17:01,411 --> 00:17:03,326
Because you're the only one

354
00:17:03,370 --> 00:17:05,154
who could understand what I've been doing.

355
00:17:05,198 --> 00:17:07,026
And why is that?

356
00:17:07,069 --> 00:17:08,549
Because you're the only one who knows

357
00:17:08,592 --> 00:17:09,811
that I killed my mother.

358
00:17:10,768 --> 00:17:13,075
[glass breaking]

359
00:17:13,119 --> 00:17:15,077
CATHERINE: So...

360
00:17:15,121 --> 00:17:18,776
I get 50 points for using all my letters, and with that...

361
00:17:18,820 --> 00:17:19,777
I win again.

362
00:17:19,821 --> 00:17:21,475
Isn't that amazing?

363
00:17:21,518 --> 00:17:23,868
Hold it. I don't know that word.

364
00:17:23,912 --> 00:17:27,089
Given how you clean this house, I am not surprised.

365
00:17:27,133 --> 00:17:28,569
[doorbell rings]

366
00:17:28,612 --> 00:17:30,223
I'll get it.

367
00:17:30,266 --> 00:17:31,876
Like you have a choice.

368
00:17:31,920 --> 00:17:34,662
Papa, this game is called Scrabble.

369
00:17:34,705 --> 00:17:36,098
It's so much fun.

370
00:17:36,142 --> 00:17:37,708
Once you get better,

371
00:17:37,752 --> 00:17:39,623
we're going to play every night. Hmm?

372
00:17:39,667 --> 00:17:41,669
Boy, you're really giving him something to live for.

373
00:17:41,712 --> 00:17:44,237
Uh... the dry cleaner's here.

374
00:17:44,280 --> 00:17:47,153
At the front door?

375
00:17:47,196 --> 00:17:49,590
Why do we even have a servants' entrance?

376
00:17:50,852 --> 00:17:52,114
Hey, everybody.

377
00:17:52,158 --> 00:17:55,117
CATHERINE: Scooter, right on time.

378
00:17:55,161 --> 00:17:56,336
I'm never late for the movies.

379
00:17:56,379 --> 00:17:58,468
Isabel...

380
00:17:58,512 --> 00:18:00,035
-where did I leave my purse? -I'm not sure.

381
00:18:01,254 --> 00:18:03,778
-[Rita clears throat] -I'll help you find it.

382
00:18:06,955 --> 00:18:08,826
What are you doing?

383
00:18:08,870 --> 00:18:10,915
-Getting ready to seduce Catherine. -Shh.

384
00:18:13,004 --> 00:18:15,268
Not in front of her father.

385
00:18:16,747 --> 00:18:18,880
Getting Catherine in the sack, that's what you wanted, right?

386
00:18:18,923 --> 00:18:20,403
Well, that was before you cheated on me.

387
00:18:20,447 --> 00:18:21,404
Oh, you'll get over it.

388
00:18:21,448 --> 00:18:22,840
Especially once you got photos

389
00:18:22,884 --> 00:18:24,233
of me and Catherine doing naked-naughty things.

390
00:18:24,277 --> 00:18:25,234
[sighs]

391
00:18:25,278 --> 00:18:26,670
How long will it take?

392
00:18:26,714 --> 00:18:27,845
A few days.

393
00:18:27,889 --> 00:18:29,020
Of course, it would be easier

394
00:18:29,064 --> 00:18:30,413
if I had my old apartment back.

395
00:18:31,719 --> 00:18:33,677
On one condition.

396
00:18:35,897 --> 00:18:37,594
No more waitresses.

397
00:18:37,638 --> 00:18:39,030
I promise.

398
00:18:39,074 --> 00:18:40,249
So...

399
00:18:40,293 --> 00:18:42,251
did you miss me?

400
00:18:42,295 --> 00:18:44,253
You know I have.

401
00:18:44,297 --> 00:18:45,428
CATHERINE: I found my purse.

402
00:18:45,472 --> 00:18:47,691
Oh, swell.

403
00:18:50,390 --> 00:18:51,826
Don't worry, Papa.

404
00:18:51,869 --> 00:18:52,914
I'll be back soon.

405
00:19:00,008 --> 00:19:01,879
[Rita chuckling]

406
00:19:01,923 --> 00:19:03,925
Scooter and Miss Catherine?

407
00:19:03,968 --> 00:19:05,579
What the hell is going on?

408
00:19:05,622 --> 00:19:07,711
Oh, something delicious.

409
00:19:07,755 --> 00:19:10,584
Come upstairs, and I'll tell you all about it.

410
00:19:25,555 --> 00:19:28,254
-I'm so sorry about this. -It-it's all right.

411
00:19:28,297 --> 00:19:31,300
I think there's a dustpan under the sink in the kitchen.

412
00:19:31,344 --> 00:19:32,823
-Could you get it for me? -Yes. Yes.

413
00:19:32,867 --> 00:19:34,303
I'll be right back.

414
00:19:37,045 --> 00:19:39,047
YOUNG TIM: Bertram.

415
00:19:39,090 --> 00:19:41,832
Your father says you have a question for me.

416
00:19:41,876 --> 00:19:44,400
Is Mummy going to hell?

417
00:19:44,444 --> 00:19:45,749
Bertie?

418
00:19:45,793 --> 00:19:47,882
Why would you ask such a thing?

419
00:19:48,970 --> 00:19:51,712
Aunt Elsa says that's where she's going

420
00:19:51,755 --> 00:19:53,801
because of how she died.

421
00:19:53,844 --> 00:19:56,325
She should not have said that.

422
00:19:56,369 --> 00:19:59,023
But I won't lie to you.

423
00:19:59,067 --> 00:20:02,853
The Church does consider suicide to be a sin.

424
00:20:02,897 --> 00:20:05,029
But if Mummy didn't kill herself,

425
00:20:05,073 --> 00:20:07,118
she'd go straight to heaven.

426
00:20:07,162 --> 00:20:08,772
Right?

427
00:20:08,816 --> 00:20:10,600
Of course she would.

428
00:20:11,906 --> 00:20:15,039
We should probably go downstairs and join the others.

429
00:20:15,083 --> 00:20:16,215
Come on.

430
00:20:22,395 --> 00:20:25,485
I need to tell you a secret.

431
00:20:26,529 --> 00:20:28,401
BERTRAM: Here we go.

432
00:20:28,444 --> 00:20:30,316
Everything all right, Father?

433
00:20:30,359 --> 00:20:32,840
Uh. Sure.

434
00:20:32,883 --> 00:20:35,799
You must be hungry after such a long ride.

435
00:20:35,843 --> 00:20:37,801
Why don't I make you dinner,

436
00:20:37,845 --> 00:20:41,196
and we can talk then about anything you like.

437
00:20:42,458 --> 00:20:44,286
Okay?

438
00:21:06,395 --> 00:21:08,789
-Mom. -Hmm.

439
00:21:08,832 --> 00:21:10,617
Are you okay?

440
00:21:10,660 --> 00:21:12,967
Yes, dear. Why?

441
00:21:13,010 --> 00:21:15,099
You just seem a little down.

442
00:21:15,143 --> 00:21:16,623
I thought you'd be on cloud nine

443
00:21:16,666 --> 00:21:18,059
after the lunch with your new club.

444
00:21:18,102 --> 00:21:21,149
Not my club. I...

445
00:21:21,192 --> 00:21:23,107
-I didn't get in. -What?

446
00:21:23,151 --> 00:21:25,414
But the telegram?

447
00:21:25,458 --> 00:21:27,677
It was a prank.

448
00:21:27,721 --> 00:21:29,288
A prank?

449
00:21:29,331 --> 00:21:30,767
[scoffs]

450
00:21:34,336 --> 00:21:36,947
Rita deliberately humiliated me today.

451
00:21:38,558 --> 00:21:41,343
I've been sitting here for hours, trying to understand why.

452
00:21:42,649 --> 00:21:45,173
What could I possibly have done to make her hate me?

453
00:21:50,178 --> 00:21:53,050
-Mom. -Hmm?

454
00:21:53,094 --> 00:21:55,357
Is that the woman who runs the Garden Club?

455
00:21:55,401 --> 00:21:57,054
Yes. That's Rita Castillo.

456
00:21:58,621 --> 00:22:00,362
-Do you know her? -Oh, my God.

457
00:22:00,406 --> 00:22:03,278
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

458
00:22:03,322 --> 00:22:04,714
What are you going on about?

459
00:22:04,758 --> 00:22:06,847
Mom, what Rita did,

460
00:22:06,890 --> 00:22:08,631
it's not 'cause she hates you.

461
00:22:10,416 --> 00:22:11,808
It's 'cause she hates me.

462
00:22:20,077 --> 00:22:22,210
[crowd chattering]

463
00:22:23,994 --> 00:22:27,607
So, do you like living in L.A., or do you miss Texas?

464
00:22:27,650 --> 00:22:30,349
Well, I-I certainly miss my friends,

465
00:22:30,392 --> 00:22:31,915
and my job in my church.

466
00:22:31,959 --> 00:22:35,266
But right now, my place is here, with Papa.

467
00:22:35,310 --> 00:22:36,833
At least when you do go back,

468
00:22:36,877 --> 00:22:38,531
he'll have his wife to take care of him.

469
00:22:38,574 --> 00:22:40,359
[scoffs] His wife.

470
00:22:40,402 --> 00:22:42,361
She's the reason I'm here.

471
00:22:42,404 --> 00:22:44,101
I don't trust her one bit.

472
00:22:44,145 --> 00:22:45,842
How come?

473
00:22:45,886 --> 00:22:48,410
Well, Rita married him for his money.

474
00:22:48,454 --> 00:22:51,457
And I'm sure she's been cheating on him this whole time.

475
00:22:51,500 --> 00:22:54,460
Oh. Uh...

476
00:22:54,503 --> 00:22:56,549
any idea who with?

477
00:22:56,592 --> 00:22:57,767
No.

478
00:22:57,811 --> 00:22:59,378
But once I find out,

479
00:22:59,421 --> 00:23:02,555
I'll make Rita and her gigolo very sorry.

480
00:23:02,598 --> 00:23:04,687
[chuckles nervously]

481
00:23:04,731 --> 00:23:05,862
Hey.

482
00:23:05,906 --> 00:23:07,908
Do you have time to get some ice cream?

483
00:23:07,951 --> 00:23:09,605
Oh. That would be lovely.

484
00:23:09,649 --> 00:23:11,520
[both chuckling]

485
00:23:12,521 --> 00:23:14,088
Hi. Uh, two, please.

486
00:23:14,131 --> 00:23:17,178
I knew Scooter was having an affair with a married woman,

487
00:23:17,221 --> 00:23:19,702
but I kept seeing him, until I got jealous.

488
00:23:19,746 --> 00:23:21,965
Then I followed him to a restaurant and dumped him.

489
00:23:22,009 --> 00:23:23,097
In front of Rita.

490
00:23:23,140 --> 00:23:24,533
Which felt good at the time,

491
00:23:24,577 --> 00:23:26,970
but I had no idea she was in your club.

492
00:23:27,014 --> 00:23:29,756
And I certainly didn't know that she would take it out on you.

493
00:23:29,799 --> 00:23:31,018
Oh, Mom.

494
00:23:31,061 --> 00:23:33,020
I'm so sorry she's hurt you.

495
00:23:33,063 --> 00:23:34,891
Mom?

496
00:23:34,935 --> 00:23:36,589
Can you say something?

497
00:23:36,632 --> 00:23:39,461
So Rita's cheating on her husband.

498
00:23:40,549 --> 00:23:42,290
Uh... yeah.

499
00:23:42,333 --> 00:23:44,640
With an out-of-work actor.

500
00:23:45,772 --> 00:23:48,470
I'm surprised she'd do such a thing.

501
00:23:48,514 --> 00:23:50,733
But not that I would?

502
00:23:50,777 --> 00:23:52,474
Oh, well, you're not married.

503
00:23:52,518 --> 00:23:54,520
I mean, shame on you and all that,

504
00:23:54,563 --> 00:23:56,260
but we're talking about Rita.

505
00:23:56,304 --> 00:23:58,219
Okay.

506
00:23:58,262 --> 00:24:00,613
It all makes sense now.

507
00:24:00,656 --> 00:24:02,484
Of course she doesn't want me in the club.

508
00:24:02,528 --> 00:24:05,008
Not only does she hate me because I'm your mother,

509
00:24:05,052 --> 00:24:06,488
but she's afraid of what I might know,

510
00:24:06,532 --> 00:24:08,185
what I might say to the other ladies.

511
00:24:08,229 --> 00:24:10,492
You should say something.

512
00:24:10,536 --> 00:24:12,494
Let the whole town know the truth about her.

513
00:24:12,538 --> 00:24:15,715
That she's a horrible, vindictive woman.

514
00:24:15,758 --> 00:24:17,499
No.

515
00:24:17,543 --> 00:24:20,415
No, now is not the time for spite.

516
00:24:20,459 --> 00:24:23,244
If I am to have satisfaction,

517
00:24:23,287 --> 00:24:25,855
I must be forgiving.

518
00:24:29,119 --> 00:24:30,773
You would forgive Rita?

519
00:24:30,817 --> 00:24:32,906
After everything she's done to you?

520
00:24:32,949 --> 00:24:35,474
What does Proverbs say?

521
00:24:36,562 --> 00:24:40,261
"If thy enemy be hungry, give her food to eat.

522
00:24:40,304 --> 00:24:43,482
"If she thirsts, give her water to drink.

523
00:24:45,440 --> 00:24:49,096
"For thou shalt heap hot coals upon her head,

524
00:24:49,139 --> 00:24:53,535
and the Lord will reward thee."

525
00:24:55,581 --> 00:24:57,931
This is why I love the Bible.

526
00:25:03,589 --> 00:25:05,112
SCOOTER: So...

527
00:25:05,155 --> 00:25:07,157
you didn't mention a husband waiting for you back home.

528
00:25:07,201 --> 00:25:08,419
Are you a widow?

529
00:25:09,508 --> 00:25:11,771
No. I never married.

530
00:25:11,814 --> 00:25:13,947
I bet you were asked, though, huh?

531
00:25:13,990 --> 00:25:15,426
Plenty of times.

532
00:25:15,470 --> 00:25:17,603
Yes, I... I was asked.

533
00:25:17,646 --> 00:25:19,909
Turned him down, huh?

534
00:25:19,953 --> 00:25:22,216
Something like that.

535
00:25:23,217 --> 00:25:24,871
Good for you.

536
00:25:24,914 --> 00:25:26,525
It's better to wait for the right guy.

537
00:25:26,568 --> 00:25:28,570
Don't worry.

538
00:25:28,614 --> 00:25:29,876
He'll show up.

539
00:25:32,966 --> 00:25:33,923
Um.

540
00:25:33,967 --> 00:25:35,272
Do I...

541
00:25:35,316 --> 00:25:36,839
I have something on my face?

542
00:25:36,883 --> 00:25:38,058
Just a little bit.

543
00:25:38,101 --> 00:25:39,059
No, no, no.

544
00:25:39,102 --> 00:25:40,495
Let me.

545
00:25:43,803 --> 00:25:46,545
So, uh, are you enjoying your retirement, Father?

546
00:25:46,588 --> 00:25:49,504
Yes. Not to say that I don't miss my parish

547
00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:50,810
and the people in it.

548
00:25:50,853 --> 00:25:53,116
Yeah. Well, everyone adored you.

549
00:25:53,160 --> 00:25:55,728
You were certainly there for me when I needed you the most.

550
00:25:55,771 --> 00:25:59,775
You were a sweet child put in an unimaginable position.

551
00:25:59,819 --> 00:26:04,388
I'm glad I was able to provide some comfort.

552
00:26:04,432 --> 00:26:08,654
I still remember how you calmed me down that awful day.

553
00:26:08,697 --> 00:26:10,960
You said God would understand what I'd done. [chuckles]

554
00:26:11,004 --> 00:26:14,007
I wish He'd explain that to my wife.

555
00:26:14,050 --> 00:26:19,447
You-you told Alma about how you helped your mother?

556
00:26:19,490 --> 00:26:21,144
-Oh, no. -Oh, good.

557
00:26:21,188 --> 00:26:22,319
It's in the past.

558
00:26:22,363 --> 00:26:24,104
Leave it there.

559
00:26:24,147 --> 00:26:26,497
But she did find out about the others I've helped.

560
00:26:27,542 --> 00:26:28,935
Others?

561
00:26:28,978 --> 00:26:30,110
Yes.

562
00:26:30,153 --> 00:26:32,678
Alma isn't moved to help the afflicted.

563
00:26:32,721 --> 00:26:34,810
She doesn't grasp why I need to.

564
00:26:34,854 --> 00:26:37,204
Compassion is always kind.

565
00:26:37,247 --> 00:26:39,032
No matter how it's delivered.

566
00:26:39,075 --> 00:26:41,208
She never had anyone to teach her that.

567
00:26:41,251 --> 00:26:42,557
But luckily, I did.

568
00:26:42,601 --> 00:26:44,211
Did you say "others"?

569
00:26:44,254 --> 00:26:45,734
Well...

570
00:26:45,778 --> 00:26:47,823
I've met so many people like my mother.

571
00:26:47,867 --> 00:26:50,783
Sick. Tormented.

572
00:26:50,826 --> 00:26:53,612
All ready to leave this world behind.

573
00:26:53,655 --> 00:26:55,570
And I've helped them, too.

574
00:26:55,614 --> 00:26:58,747
The same way you helped your mother?

575
00:26:58,791 --> 00:27:00,488
-Yes. -[gasps]

576
00:27:00,531 --> 00:27:02,838
Do you recall what you said to me?

577
00:27:02,882 --> 00:27:04,753
You said, "God will forgive those

578
00:27:04,797 --> 00:27:06,320
who relieve the suffering of others."

579
00:27:06,363 --> 00:27:07,930
I've always remembered that.

580
00:27:10,411 --> 00:27:12,500
I see. [chuckles]

581
00:27:30,736 --> 00:27:32,912
[coughing]

582
00:27:36,785 --> 00:27:39,179
You were saying?

583
00:27:40,746 --> 00:27:42,922
Not only did I get fired,

584
00:27:42,965 --> 00:27:45,402
I had to tell my mom about my fling with Scooter.

585
00:27:45,446 --> 00:27:49,102
I begged her not to tell my dad, but I know she will.

586
00:27:49,145 --> 00:27:52,061
So I think it's safe to say this has been the lousiest day

587
00:27:52,105 --> 00:27:53,889
of my...

588
00:27:55,935 --> 00:27:57,850
I'm pouring my heart out here

589
00:27:57,893 --> 00:27:59,721
and you're grinning like a hyena.

590
00:27:59,765 --> 00:28:01,288
Why?

591
00:28:01,331 --> 00:28:02,724
I was just thinking.

592
00:28:02,768 --> 00:28:04,813
About what?

593
00:28:05,901 --> 00:28:07,511
Well, during the war, me and my buddies

594
00:28:07,555 --> 00:28:09,688
would talk about what it would be like when we got back home.

595
00:28:10,776 --> 00:28:14,431
None of us expected anything fancy.

596
00:28:14,475 --> 00:28:17,652
Just a quiet life with a nice girl.

597
00:28:19,436 --> 00:28:23,049
Then I got hurt, and my girl dumped me.

598
00:28:24,180 --> 00:28:27,227
I felt real sorry for myself.

599
00:28:27,270 --> 00:28:30,621
And I stopped thinking about the future because...

600
00:28:30,665 --> 00:28:32,754
it didn't look bright.

601
00:28:34,364 --> 00:28:36,366
But now I'm here,

602
00:28:36,410 --> 00:28:39,500
with you,

603
00:28:39,543 --> 00:28:42,503
and I don't feel sorry for myself anymore.

604
00:28:44,157 --> 00:28:45,985
Anyway...

605
00:28:46,028 --> 00:28:47,943
that's why I was smiling.

606
00:28:49,292 --> 00:28:50,772
But go on.

607
00:28:50,816 --> 00:28:52,774
Keep telling me about your problems.

608
00:28:53,819 --> 00:28:55,908
Now that I think about it,

609
00:28:55,951 --> 00:28:58,171
I don't really have any.

610
00:29:05,134 --> 00:29:07,006
[doorbell rings]

611
00:29:10,705 --> 00:29:12,272
Hello.

612
00:29:12,315 --> 00:29:15,405
Could you tell Mrs. Castillo Alma Fillcot is here to see her?

613
00:29:15,449 --> 00:29:17,451
I'm sorry. She's busy right now.

614
00:29:17,494 --> 00:29:19,714
Oh, I think she'll want to see me.

615
00:29:26,503 --> 00:29:28,375
Oh, hello.

616
00:29:28,418 --> 00:29:30,551
Mr. Castillo?

617
00:29:32,422 --> 00:29:34,033
We met once.

618
00:29:34,076 --> 00:29:36,383
At a function.

619
00:29:36,426 --> 00:29:38,211
Alma Fillcot.

620
00:29:41,170 --> 00:29:43,172
[clears throat]

621
00:29:44,217 --> 00:29:45,827
I heard you had a nasty stroke.

622
00:29:45,871 --> 00:29:47,873
Is your recovery going well?

623
00:29:48,917 --> 00:29:50,440
[footsteps approach]

624
00:29:50,484 --> 00:29:52,138
-Mrs. Fillcot? -Hmm?

625
00:29:52,181 --> 00:29:53,704
Mrs. Castillo will see you upstairs.

626
00:29:53,748 --> 00:29:55,837
[gasps softly] Um...

627
00:29:55,881 --> 00:29:57,839
It-it was lovely to chat with you.

628
00:30:01,974 --> 00:30:03,932
Okay.

629
00:30:03,976 --> 00:30:05,847
[clears throat] Thank you.

630
00:30:26,781 --> 00:30:27,782
Hello?

631
00:30:27,826 --> 00:30:28,870
RITA: That's Carlo's room.

632
00:30:28,914 --> 00:30:31,830
I'm in my bedroom, in the back.

633
00:30:36,922 --> 00:30:38,662
Oh.

634
00:30:38,706 --> 00:30:40,839
Beautiful dressing room.

635
00:30:40,882 --> 00:30:43,406
What can I do for you, Alma?

636
00:30:44,668 --> 00:30:46,888
I'd like to talk about what happened today.

637
00:30:46,932 --> 00:30:48,020
Oh.

638
00:30:48,063 --> 00:30:49,935
I know you were embarrassed, but, uh...

639
00:30:49,978 --> 00:30:52,372
I already apologized for the mistake.

640
00:30:52,415 --> 00:30:54,243
The "mistake."

641
00:30:55,244 --> 00:30:57,029
[chuckles]

642
00:30:57,072 --> 00:30:59,205
What are you smiling about?

643
00:31:00,293 --> 00:31:02,164
When we spoke in my kitchen the other day,

644
00:31:02,208 --> 00:31:04,514
I felt that we were finally getting to know one another.

645
00:31:04,558 --> 00:31:05,951
I was wrong.

646
00:31:05,994 --> 00:31:07,866
If you truly knew me, you'd know

647
00:31:07,909 --> 00:31:10,564
that you can trust me with your secrets.

648
00:31:11,608 --> 00:31:12,827
What secrets?

649
00:31:14,394 --> 00:31:17,527
To be clear, when we spoke, I knew nothing about you and...

650
00:31:17,571 --> 00:31:19,660
Oh, what is his name?

651
00:31:19,703 --> 00:31:21,009
Scooter.

652
00:31:21,053 --> 00:31:23,185
Dee only told me that story today.

653
00:31:23,229 --> 00:31:25,709
I was sorry to hear how rude she'd been to you.

654
00:31:25,753 --> 00:31:27,668
I did raise her better than that.

655
00:31:27,711 --> 00:31:29,844
As for your friendship with this...

656
00:31:29,888 --> 00:31:32,238
very handsome young actor...

657
00:31:32,281 --> 00:31:34,936
no one will hear a word about it from me.

658
00:31:34,980 --> 00:31:37,591
Friends don't tattle on friends.

659
00:31:37,634 --> 00:31:38,940
But...

660
00:31:38,984 --> 00:31:41,638
I do hope that you'll honor your promise

661
00:31:41,682 --> 00:31:43,423
and get me into the club.

662
00:31:43,466 --> 00:31:45,555
I know that you've already accepted Ada,

663
00:31:45,599 --> 00:31:48,602
but surely the rules can be bent a little bit.

664
00:31:48,645 --> 00:31:50,821
For an extra seat at the table.

665
00:31:52,998 --> 00:31:54,869
For a friend.

666
00:31:57,654 --> 00:31:59,134
[chuckling]

667
00:32:00,309 --> 00:32:03,225
Oh, Alma. [laughs]

668
00:32:03,269 --> 00:32:05,924
How masterful you are.

669
00:32:05,967 --> 00:32:09,057
How cleverly you've cornered me into...

670
00:32:10,102 --> 00:32:11,799
...accepting you.

671
00:32:11,842 --> 00:32:13,714
I detect a note of sarcasm.

672
00:32:14,758 --> 00:32:17,544
You think you can waltz in here

673
00:32:17,587 --> 00:32:19,415
and threaten me in my own home?

674
00:32:19,459 --> 00:32:20,982
I wasn't making threats.

675
00:32:21,026 --> 00:32:22,331
I was offering friendship.

676
00:32:22,375 --> 00:32:24,638
[laughs] I don't want your fucking friendship.

677
00:32:24,681 --> 00:32:27,380
If I were you,

678
00:32:27,423 --> 00:32:30,600
I would think very carefully before speaking to me that way.

679
00:32:30,644 --> 00:32:32,385
[scoffs] You can't touch me, Alma.

680
00:32:32,428 --> 00:32:35,083
I made sure of that.

681
00:32:35,127 --> 00:32:37,390
Why do you think I embarrassed you today at lunch?

682
00:32:40,306 --> 00:32:42,612
I was making sure that if you spread

683
00:32:42,656 --> 00:32:44,484
any gossip about me, people would say,

684
00:32:44,527 --> 00:32:47,574
"Oh, you can't listen to what Alma says about Rita.

685
00:32:47,617 --> 00:32:50,881
She's hated her ever since that humiliating lunch."

686
00:32:50,925 --> 00:32:52,883
[chuckles]

687
00:32:52,927 --> 00:32:56,191
No one will ever believe a word you say about me.

688
00:33:01,240 --> 00:33:03,546
Grace will believe me.

689
00:33:03,590 --> 00:33:05,722
-She'll back me up. -[chuckles]

690
00:33:05,766 --> 00:33:08,856
Oh, Grace won't back you up.

691
00:33:08,899 --> 00:33:12,512
You see, she knows that I know

692
00:33:12,555 --> 00:33:15,384
about the tawdry affair she's been having.

693
00:33:15,428 --> 00:33:17,169
Grace is having an affair?

694
00:33:17,212 --> 00:33:19,084
With who?

695
00:33:19,127 --> 00:33:22,957
Oh, I'm holding on to that little tidbit for security.

696
00:33:23,001 --> 00:33:24,480
But my point is,

697
00:33:24,524 --> 00:33:28,136
Grace won't lift a finger to protect you.

698
00:33:28,180 --> 00:33:29,964
No.

699
00:33:30,008 --> 00:33:32,053
You can't hurt me, Alma.

700
00:33:32,097 --> 00:33:34,925
Oh, but I can hurt you.

701
00:33:34,969 --> 00:33:38,581
And that gob of pudding you call a daughter...

702
00:33:38,625 --> 00:33:41,715
So you did get her fired.

703
00:33:41,758 --> 00:33:44,196
Oh, and I can do so much more.

704
00:33:44,239 --> 00:33:47,025
Think of the rumors I can spread about her.

705
00:33:48,069 --> 00:33:50,202
Oh, and your husband...

706
00:33:51,246 --> 00:33:52,508
With one phone call,

707
00:33:52,552 --> 00:33:55,511
I can destroy his entire practice.

708
00:33:55,555 --> 00:33:57,426
[scoffs]

709
00:33:57,470 --> 00:33:59,298
How horrible you are.

710
00:34:01,517 --> 00:34:03,345
To think I ever admired you.

711
00:34:03,389 --> 00:34:05,086
I don't want your admiration.

712
00:34:05,130 --> 00:34:07,001
Mm-mm.

713
00:34:08,959 --> 00:34:10,657
I want your fear.

714
00:34:10,700 --> 00:34:13,094
And now that I have it,

715
00:34:13,138 --> 00:34:15,662
get the hell out of my house.

716
00:34:42,950 --> 00:34:45,170
-[insects trilling] -[bird calling]

717
00:34:49,130 --> 00:34:51,001
[gasps] Mr. Carlo.

718
00:34:51,045 --> 00:34:52,699
I was listening to the radio, and I fell asleep.

719
00:34:52,742 --> 00:34:54,831
I'm so sorry. Are you okay?

720
00:34:54,875 --> 00:34:56,268
You poor thing.

721
00:34:56,311 --> 00:34:59,140
Let's get you to bed before Miss Catherine gets home.

722
00:34:59,184 --> 00:35:01,577
She will be so angry with me.

723
00:35:06,887 --> 00:35:08,889
-[panting] -[laughing]

724
00:35:10,499 --> 00:35:11,674
Thank you.

725
00:35:11,718 --> 00:35:13,720
Thank you for a wonderful evening.

726
00:35:13,763 --> 00:35:15,852
I haven't laughed like that in a long time.

727
00:35:15,896 --> 00:35:17,680
Uh, maybe we should do it again some night.

728
00:35:17,724 --> 00:35:19,421
Have dinner or something?

729
00:35:20,466 --> 00:35:22,120
[stammers]

730
00:35:22,163 --> 00:35:25,166
Why are you so anxious to spend time with an old lady like me?

731
00:35:25,210 --> 00:35:26,994
Oh, I'm not anxious.

732
00:35:27,037 --> 00:35:28,517
It's just...

733
00:35:28,561 --> 00:35:30,302
you know...

734
00:35:30,345 --> 00:35:31,477
you're nice.

735
00:35:31,520 --> 00:35:33,087
Hmm.

736
00:35:33,131 --> 00:35:35,698
Is that the only reason?

737
00:35:35,742 --> 00:35:37,744
Also...

738
00:35:37,787 --> 00:35:40,921
you're a dame who doesn't know how beautiful she is.

739
00:35:42,227 --> 00:35:43,967
I really dig that.

740
00:35:47,667 --> 00:35:49,669
Call you tomorrow.

741
00:35:55,631 --> 00:35:57,155
Hmm.

742
00:35:59,853 --> 00:36:02,203
A guy who washes dishes.

743
00:36:02,247 --> 00:36:05,206
-Boy, I hit the mother lode. -[chuckles]

744
00:36:05,250 --> 00:36:06,599
I'm just glad we got through a date

745
00:36:06,642 --> 00:36:07,861
that didn't end up at the hospital.

746
00:36:07,904 --> 00:36:09,602
[laughs]

747
00:36:13,649 --> 00:36:15,477
[sighs]

748
00:36:16,478 --> 00:36:18,524
So. Um...

749
00:36:23,964 --> 00:36:25,444
So...

750
00:36:25,487 --> 00:36:26,749
Um...

751
00:36:27,881 --> 00:36:29,709
Thanks for coming over.

752
00:36:29,752 --> 00:36:31,972
It was a real good night.

753
00:36:33,016 --> 00:36:34,888
Does it have to be over?

754
00:36:35,932 --> 00:36:37,107
Meaning what?

755
00:36:37,151 --> 00:36:39,284
Meaning...

756
00:36:39,327 --> 00:36:41,155
I want to see your bedroom.

757
00:36:41,199 --> 00:36:42,287
Oh.

758
00:36:42,330 --> 00:36:43,549
Um...

759
00:36:43,592 --> 00:36:44,985
What's wrong?

760
00:36:47,509 --> 00:36:49,207
I don't think that's a good idea.

761
00:36:49,250 --> 00:36:50,947
Why not?

762
00:36:50,991 --> 00:36:53,298
No. It's not you.

763
00:36:54,386 --> 00:36:55,517
It's me.

764
00:36:56,518 --> 00:36:57,911
Look, I haven't...

765
00:36:57,954 --> 00:37:01,393
I haven't been with somebody since before the war.

766
00:37:02,785 --> 00:37:04,352
Because of...

767
00:37:04,396 --> 00:37:06,180
Yeah.

768
00:37:06,224 --> 00:37:08,443
I'm embarrassed.

769
00:37:10,228 --> 00:37:12,621
What that land mine did to my body...

770
00:37:13,666 --> 00:37:15,450
Vern. No.

771
00:37:17,060 --> 00:37:18,714
It doesn't matter.

772
00:37:39,257 --> 00:37:41,084
Look, I should warn you.

773
00:37:41,128 --> 00:37:42,738
Don't speak.

774
00:37:52,357 --> 00:37:54,272
My chest isn't too bad.

775
00:37:54,315 --> 00:37:57,927
It's mostly my leg and my back and my...

776
00:37:57,971 --> 00:38:00,190
-Shh. -My neck and...

777
00:38:29,089 --> 00:38:31,091
♪

778
00:39:07,040 --> 00:39:09,042
[heavy breathing]

779
00:39:18,007 --> 00:39:21,794
Well, then I helped Ira West die.

780
00:39:21,837 --> 00:39:24,144
Um... he had tuberculosis.

781
00:39:24,187 --> 00:39:26,407
After him was Sue Cork.

782
00:39:26,451 --> 00:39:27,756
She had suffered a stroke.

783
00:39:27,800 --> 00:39:29,149
Um, then I helped...

784
00:39:29,192 --> 00:39:30,933
I don't need to hear about every victim.

785
00:39:30,977 --> 00:39:32,413
Just give me the grand total.

786
00:39:32,457 --> 00:39:35,155
Oh, uh. Right. Hmm.

787
00:39:37,505 --> 00:39:38,637
Twenty-six.

788
00:39:38,680 --> 00:39:41,074
You murdered 26 people?

789
00:39:41,117 --> 00:39:42,945
Sweet Jesus!

790
00:39:42,989 --> 00:39:44,294
I thought you'd understand.

791
00:39:44,338 --> 00:39:46,296
You were so kind to me after I helped my mother.

792
00:39:46,340 --> 00:39:47,602
You were a child!

793
00:39:47,646 --> 00:39:49,865
Six is too young to know right from wrong.

794
00:39:49,909 --> 00:39:52,868
I hoped you'd figure it out by the time you were ten,

795
00:39:52,912 --> 00:39:54,043
let alone 40.

796
00:39:54,087 --> 00:39:56,829
You've got to stop this madness.

797
00:39:56,872 --> 00:39:57,960
Bertram, promise me.

798
00:39:58,004 --> 00:39:59,701
I'm trying, but it's hard.

799
00:39:59,745 --> 00:40:00,702
What's hard?

800
00:40:00,746 --> 00:40:02,356
You get up. You go to work.

801
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:04,271
You don't kill. You come home.

802
00:40:04,314 --> 00:40:06,404
Do you think I want to feel this way?

803
00:40:07,448 --> 00:40:09,668
Every day I leave my house,

804
00:40:09,711 --> 00:40:13,062
and I see all the people in pain.

805
00:40:13,106 --> 00:40:15,456
On the streets, in cafés.

806
00:40:15,500 --> 00:40:18,981
Their eyes tell me they're tired of living,

807
00:40:19,025 --> 00:40:20,983
that they yearn for death.

808
00:40:21,027 --> 00:40:23,595
To see their suffering, but to do nothing for them?

809
00:40:23,638 --> 00:40:25,727
I can't bear it.

810
00:40:27,120 --> 00:40:28,904
-Uh... -It torments you

811
00:40:28,948 --> 00:40:31,690
the-the way your mother's pain tormented you?

812
00:40:31,733 --> 00:40:33,256
Yes!

813
00:40:33,300 --> 00:40:34,388
That's why you help them?

814
00:40:34,432 --> 00:40:36,608
Yes.

815
00:40:36,651 --> 00:40:39,132
And when you help them, Bertram,

816
00:40:39,175 --> 00:40:42,483
whose torment are you easing?

817
00:40:42,527 --> 00:40:44,485
Theirs or yours?

818
00:40:47,009 --> 00:40:48,968
You think these killings are merciful. They're not.

819
00:40:49,011 --> 00:40:50,404
They're selfish.

820
00:40:50,448 --> 00:40:52,667
You're taking human life to ease your own pain.

821
00:40:52,711 --> 00:40:54,539
So you'll feel better, for a while.

822
00:40:54,582 --> 00:40:56,105
But it never lasts, does it?

823
00:40:57,150 --> 00:40:58,891
No.

824
00:41:02,198 --> 00:41:04,679
I think this is what Alma was talking to me about.

825
00:41:04,723 --> 00:41:06,594
Then listen to her.

826
00:41:06,638 --> 00:41:08,640
God has blessed you with a good woman

827
00:41:08,683 --> 00:41:12,382
who knows the worst of you and loves you anyway.

828
00:41:12,426 --> 00:41:15,734
Heed her counsel, for the rest of your days,

829
00:41:15,777 --> 00:41:18,301
and you can't go wrong.

830
00:41:19,433 --> 00:41:21,043
All right.

831
00:41:21,087 --> 00:41:23,306
So, no more killing?

832
00:41:25,091 --> 00:41:26,396
No. I swear.

833
00:41:31,619 --> 00:41:33,316
How much of that whiskey do you intend on drinking?

834
00:41:33,360 --> 00:41:35,362
How much will keep me from remembering

835
00:41:35,405 --> 00:41:37,059
this conversation tomorrow?

836
00:41:46,460 --> 00:41:48,418
[humming]

837
00:41:48,462 --> 00:41:50,464
[continues humming]

838
00:41:53,336 --> 00:41:55,643
Someone's in a good mood.

839
00:41:55,687 --> 00:41:57,036
Yes.

840
00:41:57,079 --> 00:41:59,386
So, please, don't ruin it by speaking,

841
00:41:59,429 --> 00:42:00,779
or breathing.

842
00:42:00,822 --> 00:42:03,216
ISABEL: Here you are, Mr. Carlo.

843
00:42:04,652 --> 00:42:06,524
Good morning, Papa.

844
00:42:06,567 --> 00:42:09,004
How are you feeling today?

845
00:42:09,048 --> 00:42:11,964
He's been fidgety. I think he wanted to see you.

846
00:42:12,007 --> 00:42:13,269
Please.

847
00:42:13,313 --> 00:42:15,010
He doesn't even know his first name anymore.

848
00:42:15,054 --> 00:42:16,708
Liar.

849
00:42:16,751 --> 00:42:18,405
His mind is fine.

850
00:42:18,448 --> 00:42:21,408
When we do therapy, he obeys commands.

851
00:42:21,451 --> 00:42:22,888
-Right? -He does?

852
00:42:22,931 --> 00:42:24,324
Yes.

853
00:42:24,367 --> 00:42:25,978
He even squeezed a ball the other day in the park.

854
00:42:26,021 --> 00:42:27,980
[straining]

855
00:42:28,023 --> 00:42:29,242
What is it, Papa?

856
00:42:29,285 --> 00:42:31,374
Do you want to say something?

857
00:42:31,418 --> 00:42:33,376
[straining, mumbling]

858
00:42:33,420 --> 00:42:35,204
RITA: He's probably just bored.

859
00:42:35,248 --> 00:42:38,077
Isabel, why don't you take him outside for some fresh air?

860
00:42:39,339 --> 00:42:42,081
[straining]

861
00:42:42,124 --> 00:42:44,736
Oh, look. He's... he's moving his finger.

862
00:42:44,779 --> 00:42:45,998
What?

863
00:42:46,041 --> 00:42:47,303
Do it again, Papa.

864
00:42:49,436 --> 00:42:51,351
I think he's pointing at something.

865
00:42:51,394 --> 00:42:52,570
[mumbling]

866
00:42:54,963 --> 00:42:56,617
Is it the game?

867
00:42:56,661 --> 00:42:58,314
Do you want to play with us?

868
00:42:59,664 --> 00:43:01,709
[scoffs] Don't be ridiculous.

869
00:43:01,753 --> 00:43:03,450
He couldn't possibly...

870
00:43:05,104 --> 00:43:07,367
Is there something on the board?

871
00:43:11,719 --> 00:43:13,373
Oh! Ah.

872
00:43:13,416 --> 00:43:15,157
What the hell is wrong with you?

873
00:43:15,201 --> 00:43:17,116
I must have lost my footing. I don't know.

874
00:43:17,159 --> 00:43:20,032
Isabel, help me clean this mess.

875
00:43:20,075 --> 00:43:21,642
ISABEL: You got it.

876
00:43:29,955 --> 00:43:32,174
-[sobbing] -Oh, Mom.

877
00:43:32,218 --> 00:43:33,872
Please don't cry.

878
00:43:33,915 --> 00:43:35,438
I can't help it.

879
00:43:35,482 --> 00:43:38,485
The way Rita spoke to me was just...

880
00:43:38,528 --> 00:43:40,443
It was so demeaning.

881
00:43:40,487 --> 00:43:42,184
She's a horrible woman.

882
00:43:42,228 --> 00:43:43,838
Thank God you'll never see her again.

883
00:43:43,882 --> 00:43:48,843
Maybe one of the other botanical societies in town will have me.

884
00:43:48,887 --> 00:43:52,673
If word of my humiliation hasn't spread across Los Angeles.

885
00:43:52,717 --> 00:43:55,241
There are lots of clubs

886
00:43:55,284 --> 00:43:57,373
that would be thrilled to have you as a member.

887
00:43:59,506 --> 00:44:00,986
You're so sweet.

888
00:44:06,034 --> 00:44:07,253
We should start our day.

889
00:44:07,296 --> 00:44:09,168
You put the kettle on.

890
00:44:09,211 --> 00:44:10,343
I'll get the morning paper.

891
00:44:10,386 --> 00:44:12,127
[phone ringing]

892
00:44:13,172 --> 00:44:15,696
Uh, if that's your father...

893
00:44:15,740 --> 00:44:17,437
don't mention Rita.

894
00:44:17,480 --> 00:44:19,613
I can't handle him telling me "I told you so."

895
00:44:19,657 --> 00:44:21,049
Not yet, anyway.

896
00:44:24,400 --> 00:44:26,576
-Hello? -MAN: Dee?

897
00:44:26,620 --> 00:44:27,926
Good morning. It's Dr. Rice.

898
00:44:27,969 --> 00:44:29,579
Oh. Hi, Doc.

899
00:44:29,623 --> 00:44:31,451
The bump on my head is feeling a lot better.

900
00:44:31,494 --> 00:44:33,148
Oh, good. Good. Um...

901
00:44:33,192 --> 00:44:36,108
But actually, I'm calling because of those tests we ran.

902
00:44:36,151 --> 00:44:38,153
We discovered, uh...

903
00:44:38,197 --> 00:44:40,329
This is a bit delicate, but...

904
00:44:40,373 --> 00:44:43,289
Dee, are you aware you're pregnant?

905
00:44:44,290 --> 00:44:46,292
[gasping]

906
00:44:49,687 --> 00:44:51,689
[sniffling]

907
00:45:10,359 --> 00:45:12,535
Oh. [gasps]

908
00:45:25,723 --> 00:45:29,552
NARRATOR: As Alma looked at the ruins of her beloved garden,

909
00:45:29,596 --> 00:45:34,079
she was filled with a profound grief,

910
00:45:34,122 --> 00:45:36,821
unlike any she'd ever known.

911
00:45:39,301 --> 00:45:41,782
And then she saw the card.

912
00:45:41,826 --> 00:45:43,871
RITA: Threaten me again,

913
00:45:43,915 --> 00:45:46,526
and this will be your family.

914
00:45:46,569 --> 00:45:48,310
NARRATOR: And just like that,

915
00:45:48,354 --> 00:45:51,879
her grief was transformed into rage.

916
00:45:54,577 --> 00:45:56,101
For a moment,

917
00:45:56,144 --> 00:45:59,539
Alma wondered how she would go about punishing Rita.

918
00:46:01,759 --> 00:46:05,850
That's when this timid, awkward mouse of a woman remembered...

919
00:46:06,938 --> 00:46:09,810
...she was married to a serial killer.

920
